  "prompt": "If 500 and 1000 Rs are made illegal, how does it help to bring back black money in Swiss banks or other international banks?",
  "response": "The demonetization of 500 and 1000 Rs notes in November 2016 was aimed at addressing black money, but its effectiveness in bringing back money from Swiss or other international banks was limited. Here's a breakdown:\n\nPotential Short-Term Effects:\n1. Forced people to deposit illegal cash in banks\n2. Created a paper trail for undeclared income\n3. Some black money holders were forced to convert cash\n4. Increased digital transaction transparency\n\nLimitations:\n1. Most black money is already stored internationally\n2. Offshore accounts weren't directly impacted\n3. Cash is just one form of black money\n4. People found alternative ways to convert currency\n\nWhy It Didn't Fully Address International Black Money:\n1. Money in foreign banks wasn't physically present in India\n2. Requires international banking cooperation\n3. Complex legal procedures to repatriate funds\n4. Sophisticated money laundering techniques exist\n\nAlternative More Effective Approaches:\n1. Bilateral tax treaties\n2. Stronger international financial regulations\n3. Enhanced tax investigation mechanisms\n4. Improved financial transparency laws\n\nWhile demonetization created some disruption, it wasn't a comprehensive solution for recovering black money from international banks.",
